    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, it sounds pretty risky. The language is a bit dense though—it mentions \"losses, damages, liabilities, deficiencies, claims...\". Are there usually specific \"hidden\" things in these types of clauses that people miss? Like, are there certain ways these risks sneak up on you?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, these clauses often hide \"hidden\" traps like covering third-party claims or the acts of your own employees, which can lead to unexpected lawsuits. Some Indemnification clauses are so broad they cover even unintentional errors or even the negligence of people you didn't personally fire, making your personal and professional reputation vulnerable. Additionally, they sometimes include \"indemnification for indemnification,\" meaning you might be forced to pay for costs just to defend against your own client's claim against you. It's crucial to clarify these hidden scopes before signing, as they can transform a standard contract into a personal liability trap. You might want to negotiate a cap on liability or exclude specific categories of hidden risks.",
